text: Functional genome research on bacteria relevant for agriculture, environment and biotechnology In order to foster bacterial genome research in Germany, the Fed- eral Ministry of Education and Research (BMBF) established three German-wide competence networks eight years ago. One of these networks which is entitled “Functional genome research on bac- teria relevant for agriculture, environment and biotechnology” is co-ordinated by a competence centre located at Bielefeld Univer- sity. The progress made during the initial phase of the network’s research was published in a special issue of the Journal of Biotech- nology in 2003 (Pühler and Selbitschka, 2003). After another six years of research, the network partners agreed to present their scientiﬁc achievements in a second special issue of the Journal of Biotechnology. This follow-up special issue is composed of 16 original papers and one review article which are arranged in four sections. The ﬁrst section presents a total of three papers. Two of them deal with the development of bioinformatics tools for bac- terial genome research and one paper evaluates statistical tests for the interpretation of microarray data. The second section addresses the genomics of selected bacteria with relevance in agriculture and environment. A total of ﬁve papers deal with plant beneﬁ- cial bacteria such as the biocontrol agent Bacillus amyloliquefaciens, the symbiotic nitrogen ﬁxing bacteria Sinorhizobium meliloti and Bradyrhizobium japonicum, or the plant deleterious bacterium Xan- thomonas campestris pv. campestris. The next section comprises a total of four papers which address functional genomics of the amino acid producer Corynebacterium glutamicum. Finally, the fourth sec- tion presents ﬁve papers dealing with potent producers of natural products, actinomycetes and myxobacteria, respectively. Bioinformatics tools for bacterial genome research

The availability of appropriate bioinformatics tools is of utmost importance for the advancement of genome research. The paper of Bekel et al. presents the software tool Sequence Analysis and Management System – SAMS 2.0. The new program is designed to support the computational analysis of sequence data arising from whole genome shotgun (WGS) bacterial genome sequencing or the sequencing of expressed sequence tags (EST’s). Notably, SAMS 2.0 processes sequence data obtained by ultrafast sequencing methods such as the 454 sequence technology. For the annotation and anal- ysis of gene clusters encoding secondary metabolite production, Weber et al. developed the open source software pipeline CLUSEAN (Cluster Sequence Analyzer). The new software tool integrates stan- dard analysis tools such as Blast with speciﬁc tools for e.g. the identiﬁcation of functional domains and motifs in nonribosomal peptid synthetases. Genome research on bacteria relevant for agriculture and environment

The review of Chen et al. addresses the plant growth promot- ing Bacillus amyloliquefaciens strain FZB42 whose genome sequence was published in 2007. The genome data revealed that B. amy- loliquefaciens FZB42 devotes nearly 9% of its genetic capacity to the synthesis of lipopeptides and polyketides displaying activ- ity against fungi, bacteria and nematodes. In an accompanying paper, Chen et al. demonstrate that the polyketide difﬁdicin is active against the plant pathogen Erwinia amylovora. The dipep- tide bacilysin was also shown to inhibit growth of E. amylovora and consequently, the authors propose to use B. amyloliquefaciens strains with enhanced synthesis of difﬁdicin and/or bacilysin for the development of biocontrol agents against ﬁre blight disease. Sinorhizobium meliloti strain 1021 was one of the ﬁrst agriculturally important soil bacteria whose genome sequence was established. Since the release of the genome data in 2001, many new data were produced making an update of the previous annotation mandatory. The paper of Becker et al. describes the revised annotation and the establishment of a new web-based portal entitled RhizoGATE which can be used as an on-line resource. The paper of Hempel et al. addresses the secretome of the soybean symbiont, Bradyrhizo- bium japonicum. Mass spectrometry of secreted proteins revealed that most of them appear to belong to substrate-binding proteins of the ABC transporter family, putatively involved in nutrient uptake. The network’s research covers phytopathogenic bacteria as well. Watt and co-authors describe the effect of a low molecular weight host plant extract on the expression of virulence related genes in the plant pathogen Xanthomonas campestris pv. campestris. Inter- estingly, the presence of the extract led to an up-regulation of the secretion of degradative enzymes. Genome research on the industrially important primary metabolite producer Corynebacterium glutamicum

The Gram-positive soil bacterium Corynebacterium glutamicum is well-known for the fermentative production of amino acids at an industrial scale. Consequently, C. glutamicum is under inten- sive research for decades in order to understand the underlying genetic and metabolic principles and to exploit the knowledge to increase the yield of industrially relevant compounds. The work of Buchinger et al. addresses the master regulator of nitrogen control in C. glutamicum. A combination of transcriptome and metabolome analyses resulted in the identiﬁcation of new targets for the nitro- gen regulator, connecting nitrogen control with lysine biosynthesis and carbon metabolism. C. glutamicum is able to use a variety of sugars and organic acids as sole or additional sources of carbon and energy. Veit et al. used a combination of metabolic ﬂux and func- tional genomics analyses to study acetic acid and propionic acid utilization by C. glutamicum. The analyses revealed that acetate and propionic acid activation was accomplished by a redundant sys- tem consisting of an acetate kinase pathway and a newly identiﬁed CoA transferase. C. glutamicum can also grow on ethanol as sole or as additional carbon and energy source. The work of Auchter et al. describes the identiﬁcation and characterization of a gene encoding an acetaldehyde dehydrogenase. The analyses revealed that transcription of the newly identiﬁed gene is under the con- trol of transcriptional regulators RamA and RamB. Finally, Emer et al. present evidence that the transcriptional regulators RamA and RamB are also involved in the regulation of the C. glutamicum gene encoding aconitase. In summary, the results presented above enhance our knowledge of nitrogen and carbon control in C. glu- tamicum and thus, provide a signiﬁcant contribution to the future rational design of production strains. Genome research on the medically relevant secondary metabolite producing actinomycetes and myxobacteria

Actinomycetes and myxobacteria are potent producers of sec- ondary metabolites displaying biological activities and thus, are of enormous importance in medical therapy. Actinomycetes are used for a long time for the production of antibiotics whereas myxobacteria have previously gained much interest, in particular due to the biosynthesis of bioactive compounds with cytostatic properties. In their paper, Nolden et al. focus on the rare acti- nomycete Actinoplanes friuliensis, the producer of the lipopeptide antibiotic friulimicin. Friulimicin is active against a broad range of Gram-positive human pathogens including methicillin-resistant Enterococcus spec. and Staphylococcus aureus strains. The analy- ses led to the identiﬁcation of a pathway-speciﬁc regulator which positively regulates the majority of friulimicin biosynthetic genes. Other secondary metabolites under study are the benastatins from Streptomyces sp. which inhibit glutathion-S-transferases and induce Editorial / Journal of Biotechnology 140 (2009) 1–2

apoptosis. The work of Xu et al. describes successful attempts to construct hybrid pathways of different biosynthetic gene clus- ters. The work highlights the potential of metabolic pathways, e.g., for the generation of novel potential therapeutics. A secondary metabolite that is produced by strains of the genera Actinoplanes and Streptomyces is acarbose which inhibits alpha glucosidase. Acar- bose is of medical relevance since it is used in the treatment of patients suffering from diabetes type II. In their paper, Rockser and Wehmeier describe the identiﬁcation and characterization of the acarbose biosynthetic gene cluster from S. glaucescens. In order to characterize cytostatic bioactivities from myxobacterial extracts on Sf9 insect cells, high content microscopy was used by Jensen et al. as a screening tool. The authors conclude that the newly established assay is able to discover and characterize cytotoxic and cytostatic bioactivities of crude bacterial extracts. In the paper of Rachid et al. the genome data of Sorangium cellulosum strain Soce56 pro- vided the basis for the identiﬁcation of a transcriptional regulator of the biosynthesis of the secondary metabolite chivosazol. The authors stress the importance of genomics-guided engineering of regulatory pathways for improving metabolite yields through fer- mentation. We do hope very much that the special issue “Functional genome research on bacteria relevant for agriculture, environment and biotechnology” presents a comprehensive overview over the ongo- ing research in the Bielefeld network. We are conﬁdent that the collection of papers covering a wide range of research ﬁelds will attract the attention of the readers of the Journal of Biotechnology. Pühler, A., Selbitschka, W., 2003. Genome research on bacteria relevant for agricul- ture, environment and biotechnology. Journal of Biotechnology 134, 1–2.
